IMF needs more Lagarde
Davos – Lagarde has said she is open to serving another five years as head of the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
She should stay.
The IMF has never had a better leader than her, and the IMF’s Board should give her the chance to finish the work she started.
Lagarde took office in July 2011, inheriting a crisis-ridden institution.
The 2008 global financial crash and its economic aftermath left Western-led multilateral lending institutions and the free-market "Washington Consensus" in tatters.
Lagarde's leadership helped restore the IMF's reputation.
Many looked to her personal qualities – as they should have.
She is candid, strong, warm, and engaging.
Officials from around the world who met with her (often in delicate settings) praised her for her ability to speak truth to power while also being a sensitive listener.
For an institution leader who must negotiate agreement terms rather than dictate them, these are important qualities.
Lagarde told Europeans that their banks needed restructuring, or else they would have to build firewalls to prevent financial contagion. Difficult as it was, the Europeans did as she said.
Similarly, she loudly advocated providing IMF support to some countries – such as Greece, Pakistan, Tunisia, and Ukraine – which was crucial for global stability.
There are countless other examples.
The IMF is not known for innovation, nor is it typically passionate.
Lagarde began to change this.
In the process, she gave this institution that often prescribes bitter medicine a humane face.
For example, helping manage the Middle East refugee crisis was not originally within the IMF's purview.
But under her leadership, the IMF adjusted its plans so that the Jordanian government could allocate more funds to assist those displaced by the Syrian and Iraqi conflicts (over one million people living in refugee camps within Jordan).
Similarly, in 2014, when the West African Ebola outbreak occurred, Lagarde led the IMF to provide debt relief using its available funds to countries in crisis, allowing them to increase the salaries of doctors and nurses – a first for the IMF in using its own capital for such purposes.
Moreover, Lagarde recognized three of the most important challenges facing the world today and took action on them.
First, she strongly advocated for increasing the number of women in the workforce, setting herself as a role model for women in leadership positions.
In countries ranging from Saudi Arabia to Japan, she urged leaders to stop wasting such huge talent resources – and to realize their economic potential.
Second, under her leadership, the IMF also addressed the broader issue of income inequality.
This was not just a matter of basic fairness.
IMF research emphasizes the direct link between reducing income inequality and boosting economic growth.
While other institutions have demonstrated this connection, the IMF's status makes it more prominent and urgent.
Lagarde herself has been instrumental in promoting this idea, which is key to increasing its urgency.
Third, Lagarde played a significant role in helping the world understand the full impact of technological change – some of which will have frighteningly destructive effects.
For example, automation will continue to increase manufacturing efficiency and lower costs, but also means that the number of jobs created by economic growth will be fewer than before.
This emerging reality's political, economic, and social consequences warrant our recognition and serious study.
Under her leadership, Lagarde made the IMF central to this work.
Critics might argue that it is time for developing country representatives to lead the IMF.
After all, Lagarde is already the eleventh consecutive European to hold this position, and Europe's privilege in this regard is increasingly hard to justify in today's world.
Some might also point out that the Greek austerity program supported by the IMF did not yield sufficient results, suggesting she has become disconnected from ordinary people.
Some will point out that she faces allegations of involvement in France's financial scandal, which could divert her attention from the work at the IMF.
Following her predecessor Dominique Strauss-Kahn's deep involvement in a scandal, critics argue that the IMF must not be distracted again by a similar incident.
Let's analyze these objections one by one.
The IMF (and the World Bank) should welcome leaders from outside Europe and the US.
But the goal of ending this Western privilege is to have the leader selection process based on merit rather than political considerations.
Lagarde is the best choice for IMF chief; emerging powers like the BRICS (Brazil, Russia, India, China) did not jointly nominate an alternative.
It may also be one reason why a European was chosen as IMF head last year when the fund decided to include the renminbi in the basket of currencies determining the value of its special drawing rights.
In addition, Lagarde’s impressive political flexibility ultimately persuaded both Republican and Democratic members of the US Congress to approve IMF governance reforms that not only strengthened the fund’s arsenal against financial crises but also more accurately reflected the changing dynamics of the global economy.
For instance, the BRICS now rank among the top ten shareholders at the IMF.
On Greece, Lagarde made some personally styled candid comments – which some saw as inappropriate – last year.
But she is certainly not the one who brought economic suffering to the Greeks; her tenure at the IMF fully demonstrates that no president of the IMF has done as much to lead the institution in efforts to alleviate the pain of people in crisis.
Finally, France’s allegations against Lagarde were opposed by the French chief prosecutor, and Lagarde was at most tangentially involved.
The world needs a leader dedicated to making it safer and more prosperous.
Lagarde has proven herself to be such a leader, committed to adapting the IMF for the 21st century.
She deserves the chance to see her work through to the end.
